{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505298"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:29:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:29:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2429"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2429"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.11,0.02,0.28,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98564"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2429"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80960"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6219"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1846"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1877"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43149"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98564"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a history of morning pain and stiffness in both of her hands. She reports that her hands feel stiff for 1-2 hours in the morning. Her symptoms improve gradually as the day progresses. Physical examination reveals bilateral swelling of her metacarpophalangeal joints. Temperature is 37.5 C, blood pressure is 135/85, pulse is 89/min, and respirations are 17/min. Erythrocyte sedimentation rate is 34 mm/hr. Anti-CCP Antibody positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be involved during the course of her disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cervical spine","Lumbar spine","Sacral spine","Sacroiliac joints","Thoracic spine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with a low-grade fever, morning stiffness for \u0026gt;1 hour, elevated ESR, and involvement of metacarpophalangeal joints most likely has \u003Cstrong\u003Erheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E (RA). Rheumatoid arthritis usually involves peripheral joints (eg, knee, elbow) including metacarpophalangeal joints, metatarsophalangeal joints, proximal interphalangeal joints, and wrist joints. Distal interphalangeal joints are typically spared (an important differentiating point from osteoarthritis which usually involves distal interphalangeal joints). Rheumatoid arthritis does not usually involve the axial skeleton except the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical spine\u003C/strong\u003E. Involvement of cervical spine leads to cervical spine subluxation that presents with symptoms of spinal cord compression. The rest of the spine is not affected by RA. Sacroiliac joints can be affected by RA, but these joints are more classically involved by seronegative spondylarthritis (eg, ankylosing spondylitis).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cervical spine is the only part of the spine to be involved in rheumatoid arthritis"],"references":["Kim D, Hilibrand A. Rheumatoid Arthritis in the Cervical Spine. Journal of the American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons. 2005;13(7):463-474."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80960"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2429"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"ex